            . I am a <rs id="t18320906-377-viclabel2135" type="occupation">shoemaker</rs>
                  <join result="persNameOccupation" targOrder="Y" targets="t18320906-377-victim3097 t18320906-377-viclabel2135"></join>, and live in <placeName id="t18320906-377-crimeloc2136">Upper Marylebone-street</placeName>
                  <interp inst="t18320906-377-crimeloc2136" type="placeName" value="Upper Marylebone-street"></interp>
                  <interp inst="t18320906-377-crimeloc2136" type="type" value="crimeLocation"></interp>
                  <join result="offencePlace" targOrder="Y" targets="t18320906-377-off2133 t18320906-377-crimeloc2136"></join>. The prisoner was nearly eleven months in my employ; I gave him the materials to make four pairs of shoes, on a Saturday, and on the Monday he was taken in the act of selling a pair of shoes, which are mine, and have my mark on them - I cannot say whether they were what he had to make - I never knew any thing against him.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18320906-377-person3099">
                  PETER 
                  CANE
               <interp inst="t18320906-377-person3099" type="surname" value="CANE"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18320906-377-person3099" type="given" value="PETER"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18320906-377-person3099" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . I am a Policeman. I saw the prisoner on the 3rd of September, offering these boots to a Jew for sale - he folded them up in a handkerchief, and walked off, on seeing me; I followed him to Manchestersquare, and asked how he came by them - he said he made them for a tailor's wife; they did not fit, and he wanted to sell them; he said he lived in Clipstone-street; I found he did not live there - he begged me not to take him, and then said it was work his master gave him, and when finished, instead of taking it home, he wanted to sell it - when I got near the station, he ran off, but I never lost sight of him; he said at the office that he stole them from his employer in Tottenham-court-road, but did not know the name or number.(Property produced and sworn to).</p>
               <p>The prisoner pleaded poverty.</p>
               <p>
                  <rs id="t18320906-377-verdict2137" type="verdictDescription">
